She was student body president in a year unlike any other. A few days before graduation, we caught up with outgoing 2020–21 @ncstatesg Student Body President Melanie Flowers about her time at NC State — and surprised her with a few heartfelt messages from her peers.

Congrats to Melanie and all of our #NCState21 grads! We can't wait to see what you #ThinkAndDo next. 🐺🐾🎓

Tell us about your best friend. The person who you just met in college, but it feels like you've known them forever. The person who checks to make sure you've had enough water in a day. The one who helped you navigate grad school amidst a global pandemic.

node.text: Tell us about your best friend. The person who brings you coffee when you're up studying too late and leaves notes of encouragement on your door. The person who pushes you to be your best self and is always a shoulder to cry on. The one who made NC State feel like home. node.text:
Lupin, the corpse flower, has bloomed! (Don't y'all wish we had smell-o-vision? 😷) 

Known for a stench described as rotting flesh, this pungent plant is one of the rarest and largest in the plant kingdom. At 4 feet, 6 inches tall and 33 inches wide, Lupin's third-ever bloom is its smallest yet. Prior blooms in 2016 and 2019 both measured more than 6 feet tall and about 3 feet wide. The inflorescence will only remain open for a day or two before collapsing and restarting the life cycle. 

It took 13 years for the corpse flower living on our campus, owned by horticultural scientist Brandon Huber (@bhubzz), to bloom for the first time. Subsequent blooms occur every three to seven years. Follow @ncstatecals for more corpse flower coverage. #ThinkAndDo

node.text:
Stop and smell the... corpse flower? Soon you can, as we’re eagerly anticipating Lupin’s third bloom sometime this month (and yes, it’s named after a Harry Potter character). 

Known for the pungent odor it produces, the corpse flower has one of the largest flowering structures in the plant kingdom and heats up to human body temperature as it blooms. 🤯 

It took 13 years for the corpse flower living on our campus, owned by horticultural scientist Brandon Huber (@bhubzz), to bloom for the first time. Subsequent blooms occur every three to seven years. When it bloomed in 2016 and 2019 (seen here), the plant grew to be more than 6 feet tall.

Can you guess exactly when Lupin will bloom this year? 🤔📆 Visit the link in our bio to submit your guess for the chance to win a prize pack and see (and smell) it for yourself. Follow @ncstatecals to keep up with the latest. #Lupin2016 #ThinkAndDo
